Data Cleaning¶

In [4]:
def remove_outliers(df, column_name, threshold=2.5):
    mean_value = df[column_name].mean()
    std_value = df[column_name].std()
    df_filtered = df[abs(df[column_name] - mean_value) < threshold * std_value]
    return df_filtered
In [5]:
def clean_df(df):

    df = df[(df['tip_amount'] > 0)]
    df = df[(df['total_amount'] > 0)]
    df = df[(df['fare_amount'] > 0)]
    df = df[(df['trip_distance'] > 0.3)]

    df = remove_outliers(df, 'trip_distance')
    df = remove_outliers(df, 'tip_amount')

    df['cost_per_mile'] = df['fare_amount'] / df['trip_distance']

    df = remove_outliers(df, 'cost_per_mile')

    df = df.dropna()

    return df

Data Visualization¶

In [8]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

def plot_distributions_before_after(df_before, df_after, column_name, xlabel):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

    # Plot before removing outliers
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    sns.histplot(df_before[column_name], bins=30, kde=True, color='blue')
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {column_name} before removing outliers')
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')

    # Plot after removing outliers
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    sns.histplot(df_after[column_name], bins=30, kde=True, color='green')
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {column_name} after removing outliers')
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Hypothesis 1: Cost per Mile Amounts Differs Between Taxi Providers¶

Null Hypothesis (H0) : $\mu_1 = \mu_2$

There is no significant difference in the average cost per mile amounts between taxi trips provided by Vendor 1 and Vendor 2.

Alternative Hypothesis (H1) : $\mu_1 \neq \mu_2$

Average cost per mile amounts vary between taxi trips provided by Vendor 1 and Vendor 2.

Here, $\mu_1$ represents the population mean of the cost per mile for Vendor 1, and $\mu_2$ represents the population mean of the cost per mile for Vendor 2.

In [17]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from scipy import stats

tpep_providers = sorted(nyc_taxi['VendorID'].unique())

num_simulations = 100
accept_count = 0

alpha = 0.05
rs = 1

for _ in range(num_simulations):
    fare_by_provider = {}
    np.random.seed(rs)
    rs += 1

    for provider in tpep_providers:
        provider_data = nyc_taxi[nyc_taxi['VendorID'] == provider]['cost_per_mile']
        fare_by_provider[provider] = provider_data.sample(1000)

    t_statistic, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(*fare_by_provider.values(), equal_var=False)

    if p_value > alpha:
        accept_count += 1

proportion_accept = accept_count / num_simulations

print(f"Proportion of acceptance out of {num_simulations} simulations: {proportion_accept:.2%}")

if proportion_accept > 0.5:
    print("Reject the null hypothesis. Average cost per mile amounts vary between taxi trips provided by Vendor 1 and Vendor 2.")
else:
    print("Fail to reject the null hypothesis. There is no significant difference in the average cost per mile amounts between taxi trips provided by Vendor 1 and Vendor 2.")

Proportion of acceptance out of 100 simulations: 88.00%
Reject the null hypothesis. Average cost per mile amounts vary between taxi trips provided by Vendor 1 and Vendor 2.

Hypothesis 1 Normal Distribution Plot¶

In [14]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from scipy.stats import norm
import numpy as np

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

sns.histplot(nyc_taxi[nyc_taxi['VendorID'] == 1]['cost_per_mile'], kde=True, color='blue', bins=30, stat='density')

mu, std = norm.fit(nyc_taxi[nyc_taxi['VendorID'] == 1]['cost_per_mile'])
xmin, xmax = plt.xlim()
x = np.linspace(xmin, xmax, 100)
p = norm.pdf(x, mu, std)
plt.plot(x, p, 'k', linewidth=2)

sns.histplot(nyc_taxi[nyc_taxi['VendorID'] == 2]['cost_per_mile'], kde=True, color='red', bins=30, stat='density', alpha = 0.5)

mu, std = norm.fit(nyc_taxi[nyc_taxi['VendorID'] == 2]['cost_per_mile'])
xmin, xmax = plt.xlim()
x = np.linspace(xmin, xmax, 100)
p = norm.pdf(x, mu, std)
plt.plot(x, p, 'r', linewidth=2)

plt.title('Distribution of Cost Per Mile Amount for Vendors 1 and 2')
plt.xlabel('Cost Per Mile Amount')
plt.ylabel('Density')

plt.legend(['Vendor 1 Data', 'Vendor 1 Normal Distribution', 'Vendor 2 Data', 'Vendor 2 Normal Distribution'])
plt.show()

Hypothesis 2: Tip Amount Differs Between Taxi Providers¶

Null Hypothesis (H0) : $\mu_1 = \mu_2$

There is no significant difference in the average tip amounts between taxi trips provided by Vendor 1 and Vendor 2.

Alternative Hypothesis (H1) : $\mu_1 \neq \mu_2$

Average tip amounts vary between taxi trips provided by Vendor 1 and Vendor 2.

Here, $\mu_1$ represents the population mean of the tip amount for Vendor 1, and $\mu_2$ represents the population mean of the tip amount for Vendor 2.
